# --- Find the Flag in /etc/passwd ---
# /etc/passwd traditionally stored password hashes (before /etc/shadow).
# In this wargame level, the flag/password hash is embedded in /etc/passwd.

# --- Encrypted ---
# The encrypted value retrieved from /etc/passwd is a DES crypt(3) hash.
# This is the classic Unix password hash format — identified by its
# 13-character length and use of [a-zA-Z0-9./] characters.

# --- Crack the Hash with Hashcat ---
# Hashcat is a GPU-accelerated password recovery tool.
#
# Flags explained:
#   -m 1500   → Hash type: DES (crypt(3)), the old Unix password format
#   -a 3      → Attack mode: Brute-force (mask attack)
#   decoded.txt → Input file containing the hash to crack
#   '?l?l?l?l?l?l?l' → Mask: exactly 7 lowercase letters (?l = [a-z])
#   --show    → Don't re-crack; just display already-cracked results from the
#               potfile (hashcat's cache of previously cracked hashes)
#
# WHY BRUTE-FORCE WITH THIS MASK?
# The wargame hints that the password is 7 lowercase letters, making the
# search space 26^7 = ~8 billion combinations — feasible for DES with a GPU.
# A dictionary attack would work too, but the mask is more targeted here.
